I think this is one way to do it? I'm not entirely sure and I'm curious what the answer is. It's definitely a mathematical type problem, so there might be a better way. What you do is account for two cases. When the third to last number is 1 (it can be 1 only if x is greater than 3) and when it's not. If it is 1, you should also account for the case where the fourth to last number is not 1 (only when x is greater than 4). Add the answer for second case (when the third to last number is 1) to the end as you're treating it separately. You're treating it separately as the second to last number cannot be 1, so the possibilities where the third to last number are 1 need to be considered differently. You're multiplying n-1 until then, as you can't reuse the same number as before.
```
    public int waysCities(int n, int x){
        int factor = n-1;
        int total = factor;
        int lastTotalBeforeOne = 0;
        int beforeLastOne = 0;
        for(int i=1;i<x-2;i++){
            if(i == x-3){
                lastTotalBeforeOne = (x > 4) ? (total/(n-1))*(n-2) : total;
                factor = n-2;
            }
            total*=factor;
        }
        if(x > 3){
            lastTotalBeforeOne*=(n-1);
        }
        total *= (n-2);
        total += lastTotalBeforeOne;
        return total;
    }
```
